            <fr:title text="Drinfeld double">Drinfeld double</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/misc-0002/" title="Hopf algebra" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/misc-0002/" display-uri="misc-0002" type="local">Hopf algebra</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> with <fr:link href="/forest/misc-0003/" title="antipode of a Hopf algebra" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/misc-0003/" display-uri="misc-0003" type="local">invertible antipode</fr:link>, we construct another Hopf algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D(H)]]></fr:tex> on the vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(H^\textrm {op})^\circ  \otimes  H]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^\textrm {op}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link href="/forest/misc-0008/" title="opposite Hopf algebra" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/misc-0008/" display-uri="misc-0008" type="local">opposite Hopf algebra</fr:link>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^\circ ]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link href="/forest/misc-0009/" title="duals of Hopf algebras" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/misc-0009/" display-uri="misc-0009" type="local">Sweedler dual</fr:link>. We define the unit to be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1 \otimes  1]]></fr:tex>, the counit as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon (f \otimes  a) = \epsilon (a) \cdot  f(1)]]></fr:tex>, and the antipode <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S^D(f \otimes  a) = S^\circ  (f) \otimes  S(a)]]></fr:tex>. The comultiplication <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\Delta ^D (f \otimes  a) = \sum _{i j} (g_i \otimes  b_j) \otimes  (h_i \otimes  c_j)]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta ^\circ  (f) = \sum _i g_i \otimes  h_i]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta  (a) = \sum _j b_j \otimes  c_j]]></fr:tex>. We let
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[(f \otimes  a) \cdot  (g \otimes  b) = f \cdot  (x \mapsto  g(S^{-1}(a_{(3)}) x a_{(1)})) \otimes  a_{(2)} b.]]></fr:tex>
  We can regard <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(H^\textrm {op})^\circ ]]></fr:tex> as a subalgebra of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D(H)]]></fr:tex> via <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \mapsto  f \otimes  1]]></fr:tex>, and similarly for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a \mapsto  1 \otimes  a]]></fr:tex>. Then we can write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f a = f \otimes  a]]></fr:tex>, and the algebra structure is given by the <html:em>straightening formula</html:em>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[a f = (x \mapsto  f(S^{-1}(a_{(3)})x a_{(1)})) a_{(2)}.]]></fr:tex>
  This is the <html:strong>Drinfeld double</html:strong> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  For a finite dimensional Hopf algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, the double <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D(H)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/forest/misc-0007/" title="braided Hopf algebra" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/misc-0007/" display-uri="misc-0007" type="local">braided</fr:link>, with the universal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>-matrix given by
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[R = \sum _{i} (1 \otimes  e_i) \otimes  (e^i \otimes  1)]]></fr:tex>
  where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e_i]]></fr:tex> is a set of basis of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e^i]]></fr:tex> is the dual basis in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^\circ ]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
