            <fr:title text="antipode of a Hopf algebra">antipode of a Hopf algebra</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/misc-0002/" title="Hopf algebra" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/misc-0002/" display-uri="misc-0002" type="local">Hopf algebra</fr:link>, the antipode is unique, essentially by the same argument for the uniqueness of inverses in group theory. It is also injective, which means for a finite dimensional algebra, it is automatically invertible as a linear map. However, this is not necessarily the case for infinite dimensional Hopf algebras.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  The obvious candidate for the inverse, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S^{-1} = S]]></fr:tex>, is not necessarily valid. The usual group theoretic proof that the inverse is an involution requires either swapping the label of duplicated variables, or swapping the left and right terms of a multiplication. This means <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x^{-1})^{-1} = x]]></fr:tex> holds only for cocommutative or commutative Hopf algebras.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
